<h1>WDD31 Reading List</h1>

  <h2>1. Websites</h2>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.nathan.com/">Nathan Shedroff</a> - Lots of &quot;experience design&quot; info.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.boxesandarrows.com/">Boxes and arrows</a> - Forum for latest thinking in Information Architecture</li>
<li><a href="http://www.jjg.net/ia/">JJG.net</a> - More IA resources.</li>

<li><a href="http://www.usableweb.com/">Usableweb</a> - Fantastic usability portal.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.useit.com/">UseIt</a> - Jakob Nielsen's influential musings (and self-promotion!)</li>
<li><a href="http://www-3.ibm.com/ibm/easy">IBM Ease of use</a> - Lots of user articles and resources.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.iawiki.net/">IAWiki</a> - Currently down due to a hardware problem, but should reappear soon.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.usabilitynews.com/">Usability News</a> - Latest UK news, events and jobs.</li>

</ul>

<h2>2. Books</h2>

<p>Beyer, H. &amp; Holtzblatt, K. (1998) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/1558604111/iansealycom">Contextual design.</a> Morgan Kauffman. <br>
Influential (and seriously detailed) book on contextual enquiry.</p>

<p>Cooper, A. (1999) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0672316498/iansealycom">The inmates are running the asylum</a>. Sams.<br>

The inventor of &quot;personas&quot; argues the case for user-centred design in software development.</p>

<p>Donnelly, V. (2000) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201674688/iansealycom">Designing easy-to-use websites</a>. Addison Wesley.<br>
A bit dry, but a good illustration of a very corporate, process-driven approach to web design.</p>

<p>Garrett, J.J. (2002) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0735712026/ref=pd_sim_b_dp_4/026-7588935-7214869">The Elements of User Experience</a>. New Riders.</p>

<p>Hackos, J. &amp; Redish, J. (1998) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471178314/iansealycom">User interface task analysis</a>. John Wiley &amp; Sons.<br>
THE book for task analysis and interface design, but only really for the truly dedicated! </p>

<p>Krug, S. (2000)<a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0789723107/iansealycom">Don't make me think!</a> Que.<br>

Short, easy-to-read and informative overview of web usability. A bit flippant about user testing at the end of the book, though.</p>

<p>Kuniavsky, M. (2003) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/1558609237/qid%3D1116019957/026-8843760-2836412">Observing the User Experience</a>.  Morgan Kaufman.</p>

<p>Nielsen, J (2000). <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/156205810X/iansealycom">Designing web usability: the practive of simplicity</a>. New Riders.<br>
It's Jakob. It's a classic.</p>

<p>Nielsen, J. (1994) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0125184069/iansealycom">Usability engineering</a>. Academic Press.<br>
Older Jakob, but great for understanding the &quot;usability engineering lifecycle&quot;.</p>

<p>Norman, D.A. (1998) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0262640376/iansealycom">The design of everyday things</a>. MIT Press.<br>
Great insight into how understanding human psychology can greatly affect the way we design things.</p>

<p>Raskin, J. (2000) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201379376/iansealycom">The humane interface</a>. Addison Wesley. <br>
A glimpse into the future of computer interfaces?</p>

<p>Rosenfeld, L. &amp; Morville, P. (2002) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0596000359/qid=1052421691/sr=1-1/ref=sr_1_2_1/026-7588935-7214869">Information architecture for the world wide web</a>. Second Edition. O'Reilly.<br>

The classic book on IA. Affectionately known as &quot;The Polar Bear Book&quot;. Make sure that you get the second edition - it's way more comprehensive and up-to-date than the first.</p>

<p>Reiss, E. (2000) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201725908/iansealycom">Practical information architecture</a>. Addison Wesley.<br>
Concise overview of IA.</p>

<p>Veen, J. (2001) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0789723700/iansealycom">The art &amp; science of web design</a>. New Riders.<br>

Great overview of web design. Includes illuminating chapters on user behaviour and site architecture.</p>

<p>Wodtke, C. (2002) <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0735712506/ref=pd_sim_b_dp_1/026-7588935-7214869">Information Architecture: Blueprints for the Web</a>. New Riders.</p>




